<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Selaginella bigelovii </i>is a vascular spikemoss, which is able to dry up almost completely and go dormant during the hot, dry summers. This species rapidly springs to life when moisture and cooler temperatures return, giving rise to one of its common names: resurrection plant. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance is characteristic of outcrops in much of cismontane California. It typically occurs on gently to moderately sloping slabs of rock and, over time, may form thick mats of intertwined roots and rhizomes. These mats catch soil and dust and build up enough soil to supply substrate for other herbaceous species. These stands are visible on outcrops at a distance and often show up as dark mats with emergent drying grass stems and scattered shrubs. The alliance is widespread in southern California, including the Channel Islands and Baja California. Surveys come from inland San Diego Co. north to at least Sonoma Co.; though stands are likely further in the North Coast Ranges. In the northern Sierra Nevada foothills, Klein et al. (2007) placed stands with high cover of <i>Selaginella hansenii </i>in the <i>Lasthenia californica-Plantago erecta-Vulpia microstachys </i>alliance. With further sampling in the southern foothills and other parts of California, we can better understand the relationships between <i>Selaginella</i>-dominated and annual herb-dominated vegetation. The <i>Selaginella </i>(<i>tortipila, rupestris</i>) alliance exists in the southeastern United States (NatureServe 2007a).<br/>
<br/>
This alliance has been expanded to include <i>Selaginella wallacei</i> since the publication of the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
