    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Selaginella bigelovii</i> includes the Southern California Coast (261B), Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262B), Central California Coast (262A), Mojave Desert (322A), Northern California Coast Ranges (M261B), and Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261F). The range of <i>Selaginella wallacei</i> includes the Klamath Mountains (M261A), Northern California Coast Ranges (M261B), Northern California Interior Coast Ranges (M261C), Sierra Nevada Foothills (M261Fe), and Sierra Nevada (M261Es).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac, Ae-f, Aj). Stands are extensive on volcanic and sedimentary substrates in Pinnacles National Monument (Kittel et al. 2012) on flats to steep slopes of all aspects between 300 and 900 m. Stands also appear in San Luis Obispo Co. on rock outcrops.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ag, Al-m). Stands in Marin and Sonoma Co. include both <i> Selaginella wallacei </i>(Buck-Diaz et al. 2021) and <i>Selaginella bigelovii </i>(Klein et al. 2015). Stands occur as small patches, occurring among large rocky outcrops, including from Lucas Valley Preserve to White Hill Preserve in Marin Co. and at least from Sugarloaf Ridge State Park to Austin Creek State Recreation Area and Lake Sonoma. Outcrops in this region are metamorphic, but some exist on volcanic or serpentine outcrops (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Klein et al. 2015).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb). One stand is sampled from the Lake Sonoma Recreation Area; however, more sampling is needed to understand the full extent of the alliance in this section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd). Stands of <i>Selaginella bigelovii</i> occur on rock outcrops in the Southern Granitic Foothills.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-c, Be-f). Stands are common in the Santa Monica Mountains on sedimentary and volcanic outcrops (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006). <i>Eriogonum crocatum</i> (a CNPS list 1B.2 plant) is sometimes associated with these stands. Stands appear on Santa Cruz Island.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba, Bd, Bn). Stands in central San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005) and observations in the Santa Susana and San Gabriel mountains (Horton 1941, Kirkpatrick and Hutchinson 1977) suggest that the <i>Selaginella bigelovii/ Eriogonum fasciculatum</i> association occurs throughout the section.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Rocky outcrops provide specialized habitats for both plants and animals. Some rare species are restricted to the rock crevices or the bare rock surfaces. In addition, soil stabilized by <i>Selaginella bigelovii </i>enables some cryptogams and vascular plants to colonize bare rock. Although not considered easily disturbed or threatened, impacts to vegetation on these rock outcrops may include acidification due to air pollution, physical damage due to hiking and recreational climbing, and threats from <i>Carpobrotus </i>spp., <i>Pennisetum setaceum, </i>and other invasive plants. </div>
</div>

    

    

